<subSubSection id="C3338DF3FF9CFFD3B0C670C0FCCAFDC2" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C670C0FABAFF13" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" box="[189,1336,158,185]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B0C670C0FEF7FF13" bold="true" box="[189,373,158,184]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Distribution:—</emphasis>
Endemic to Sangihe Island, 
<collectingCountry id="F33E9EE8FF9CFFD3B2CB70C0FCA3FF13" box="[688,801,158,184]" name="Indonesia" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
; currently only known from the 
<typeStatus id="549260DAFF9CFFD3B4F170C1FB38FF12" box="[1162,1210,159,185]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">type</typeStatus>
collection.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C6709CFC83FEAA" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B0C6709CFEBCFF77" bold="true" box="[189,318,194,220]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Habitat:—</emphasis>
“Hill rainforest with palms. Steep slopes with some forest trails ascending to the ridge and edges threatened by agricultural conversion”; elevation 
<specimenCount id="9D2F15F1FF9CFFD3B2C970B8FC83FEAA" box="[690,769,230,257]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" type="generic">
<quantity id="4CD1739DFF9CFFD3B2C970B8FD7EFEAA" box="[690,764,230,257]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" unit="m" value="730.0">730 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C67154FDB5FE8F" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" box="[189,567,266,292]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B0C67154FEDDFE8F" bold="true" box="[189,351,266,292]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Phenology:—</emphasis>
Flowering in April.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C67170FCCAFDC2" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B0C67170FD92FEE3" bold="true" box="[189,528,302,328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Conservation assessment:—</emphasis>
Data Deficient (DD) category of the 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B3C07170FBD5FEE3" author="IUCN &amp; Cambridge, UK" box="[955,1111,302,328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" refId="ref5935" refString="IUCN (2012) IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1, Second edition. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK." type="book" year="2012">IUCN (2012)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B41F7170FAD6FEE3" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[1124,1364,302,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B41F7170FAD6FEE3" box="[1124,1364,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from 
<specimenCount id="9D2F15F1FF9CFFD3B16D710DFE2CFEC7" box="[278,430,338,365]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
collected from Sangihe Island and there is no additional information to assess the population size. Although the island has a rugged topography because of its volcanic origin, it had been deforested by the 1920s and now only isolated fragmentary patches of natural forest remain—it is now dominated by mixed plantations, including coconut, nutmeg, clove, sago and banana (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B29C71E0FC65FE73" author="Riley, J. &amp; Wardill, J. C." box="[743,999,446,472]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="45 - 55" refId="ref6307" refString="Riley, J. &amp; Wardill, J. C. (2001) The rediscovery of Cerulean Paradise-flycatcher Eutrichomyias rowleyi on Sangihe, Indonesia. Forktail 17: 45 - 55. [https: // static 1. squarespace. com / static / 5 c 1 a 9 e 03 f 407 b 482 a 158 da 87 / t / 5 c 1 fca 7 c 40 ec 9 abd 16 b 98 e 83 / 1545587324757 / Riley-Cerulean. pdf]" type="journal article" year="2001">Riley &amp; Wardill 2001</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen was collected from the slopes of Mt Sahendaruman—the region with the most extensive remaining forest areas on Sangihe (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B48871BCFAF3FE57" author="Riley, J." box="[1267,1393,482,508]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="3 - 36" refId="ref6263" refString="Riley, J. (1997) The birds of Sangihe and Talaud, North Sulawesi. Kukila 9: 3 - 36. [http: // kukila. org / index. php / KKL / article / view / 189]" type="journal article" year="1997">Riley 1997</bibRefCitation>
) but, as recorded on the label, the forest edges are threatened by agriculture. The island is still extremely poorly known and further collections and/or observations on the plant communities of the island are required to better understand the conservation status of the island’s flora and of 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B2E87211FCC3FDC3" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[659,833,590,616]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B2E87211FCC3FDC3" box="[659,833,590,616]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3338DF3FF9CFFD3B0C6722CFC28FA46" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C6722CFB0FFD27" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" box="[189,1165,626,653]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B0C6722CFEE6FD27" bold="true" box="[189,356,626,652]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Etymology:—</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to Sangihe Island where this species is found.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C672C8FEC9FCEB" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B0C672C8FEA4FD1B" bold="true" box="[189,294,662,688]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Notes:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B15D72C8FD92FD1B" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[294,528,662,688]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B15D72C8FD92FD1B" box="[294,528,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in the genus in the combination of its climbing habit, the dense indumentum throughout and the many-flowered inflorescences. This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B46772E5FA84FD7E" authority="Merr." authorityName="Merr." box="[1052,1286,698,725]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B46772E5FB43FD7F" box="[1052,1217,698,724]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. hainanensis</emphasis>
Merr.
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B56872E4FF37FD52" author="Merrill, E. D." pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="337 - 355" refId="ref6117" refString="Merrill, E. D. (1922) Diagnoses of Hainan plants. Philippine Journal of Science. Section C, botany 21: 337 - 355. [https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 692237]" type="journal article" year="1922">Merrill 1922: 353</bibRefCitation>
), known from southern 
<collectingCountry id="F33E9EE8FF9CFFD3B1BC7280FD88FD53" box="[455,522,734,760]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">China</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F33E9EE8FF9CFFD3B2387280FD27FD53" box="[579,677,734,760]" name="Vietnam" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, in the branches and abaxial leaf surface being densely brown-hairy but differs in having 2–3(–5) subequally or unequally branched hairs, while 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B392735DFB12FCB7" box="[1001,1168,770,796]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hainanensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B392735DFB12FCB7" box="[1001,1168,770,796]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. hainanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has extremely unequally 2-branched hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C67314FAE9FC5E" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
Using the Flora Malesiana account of 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B21E7314FCB0FCCE" author="Hoogland, R. D." box="[613,818,842,869]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="404 - 431" refId="ref5890" refString="Hoogland, R. D. (1953 c) Erycibe. In: Van Steenis, C. G. G. J. (Ed.) [Convolvulaceae]. Flora Malesiana Ser. I, 4: 404 - 431." type="journal article" year="1953">Hoogland (1953c)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B3457314FBA8FCCF" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[830,1066,842,868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B3457314FBA8FCCF" box="[830,1066,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would key out to 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B48A7315FE8CFC22" authority="Prain (1896: 536)" authorityName="Prain" authorityPageNumber="536" authorityYear="1896" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strigosa">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B48A7315FAE8FCCF" box="[1265,1386,843,868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. strigosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B50B7314FE8CFC22" author="Prain, D." pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="536 - 538" refId="ref6160" refString="Prain, D. (1896) Noviciae Indicae XIII. Further notes on Indian Convolvulaceae with descriptions of three additional species. Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal. Part 2, Natural History 65: 536 - 538. [https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 37193893]" type="journal article" year="1896">Prain (1896: 536)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B1337331FD76FC23" authority="Hoogland (1953 a: 318)" authorityName="Hoogland" authorityPageNumber="318" authorityYear="1953" box="[328,756,878,905]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subsericea">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B1337331FE63FC23" box="[328,481,878,904]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. subsericea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B1917330FD76FC23" author="Hoogland, R. D." box="[490,756,878,905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="310 - 319" refId="ref5831" refString="Hoogland, R. D. (1953 a) Florae Malesianae Precursores II. The Convolvulaceae of Malaysia IX. Blumea 7 (2): 310 - 319." type="journal article" year="1953">Hoogland (1953a: 318)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
based on the acuminate anthers, sepals hairy on the outside, many-flowered inflorescences and hairy abaxial surface of the lamina. 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B3BD73CCFB00FC07" authorityName="Prain" authorityYear="1896" box="[966,1154,914,940]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strigosa">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B3BD73CCFB00FC07" box="[966,1154,914,940]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe strigosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="F33E9EE8FF9CFFD3B0F373E8FF6DFC7B" box="[136,239,950,976]" name="Malaysia" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
but has sparsely hairy (‘strigose’) leaves and axillary inforescences, whilst 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B41273E9FA86FC7B" authorityName="Hoogland" authorityYear="1953" box="[1129,1284,950,976]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subsericea">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B41273E9FA86FC7B" box="[1129,1284,950,976]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. subsericea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to Borneo and has short-sericeous hairs on the abaxial surface of the lamina and a densely hairy (‘strigose’) ovary.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C673A0FD83FA2B" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">
The Sangihe Islands are biogeographically close to northern Sulawesi and the 
<collectingCountry id="F33E9EE8FF9CFFD3B44573A0FB42FBB3" box="[1086,1216,1022,1048]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Philippines</collectingCountry>
. The only species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B0F3747CFF5DFB97" box="[136,223,1058,1084]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B0F3747CFF5DFB97" box="[136,223,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recorded from Sulawesi is 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B260747DFC59FB97" authority="C. B. Clarke (1883: 182)" authorityName="C. B. Clarke" authorityPageNumber="182" authorityYear="1883" box="[539,987,1058,1084]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="malaccensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B260747DFD46FB97" box="[539,708,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. malaccensis</emphasis>
C.B. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B282747CFC59FB97" author="Clarke, C. B." box="[761,987,1058,1084]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="179 - 228" refId="ref5433" refString="Clarke, C. B. (1883) Convolvulaceae. In: Hooker, J. D. (Ed.) Flora of British India, volume 4. L. Reeve &amp; Co Ltd., London, pp. 179 - 228. [https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 388712]" type="book chapter" year="1883">Clarke (1883: 182)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, with a disjunct distribution between the Malay Peninsula and the 
<collectingCountry id="F33E9EE8FF9CFFD3B1DE7418FDA1FBCB" box="[421,547,1094,1120]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and Sulawesi (and perhaps Java), but absent from Sumatra and Borneo. 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B52F7418FE93FB2F" authorityName="C. B. Clarke" authorityYear="1883" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="malaccensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B52F7418FE93FB2F" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Erycibe malaccensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B1D17435FDD8FB2F" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[426,602,1130,1156]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B1D17435FDD8FB2F" box="[426,602,1130,1156]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in several characters especially the leaves which are soon glabrescent, the relatively smaller laminas 5–16 × 
<quantity id="4CD1739DFF9CFFD3B26874D0FD11FB02" box="[531,659,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" unit="cm" value="4.5" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="2.5">2.5–6.5 cm</quantity>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B2DD74D1FCD4FB03" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[678,854,1166,1192]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B2DD74D1FCD4FB03" box="[678,854,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
12–17 × 
<quantity id="4CD1739DFF9CFFD3B3B274D0FBCEFB02" box="[969,1100,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="5.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" unit="cm" value="6.5" valueMax="7.5" valueMin="5.5">5.5–7.5 cm</quantity>
), the fewer 4–6(–7) secondary veins (
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B0A974EDFEFDFB67" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[210,383,1202,1228]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B0A974EDFEFDFB67" box="[210,383,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
7–10 secondary veins), the inflorescences with up to c. 20 flowers at maximum (
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B48574EDFA29FB67" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[1278,1451,1202,1228]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B48574EDFA29FB67" box="[1278,1451,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with up to c. 100 flowers), and the hairs with a distinctly longer central branch (
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B4677489FB49FB5B" authorityName="Kochaiph. &amp; Utteridge. A Habit" authorityYear="2021" box="[1052,1227,1238,1264]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sangiheensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B4677489FB49FB5B" box="[1052,1227,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sangiheensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hairs subequally or unequally branched). The only species in the 
<collectingCountry id="F33E9EE8FF9CFFD3B2FB74A4FD7CFABF" box="[640,766,1274,1300]" name="Philippines" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Philippines</collectingCountry>
with leaves that can be hairy abaxially are 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B4A674A5FA06FABF" authorityName="C. B. Clarke" authorityYear="1883" box="[1245,1412,1274,1300]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="malaccensis">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B4A674A5FA06FABF" box="[1245,1412,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. malaccensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as previously discussed), 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B1F37541FC81FA93" authority="Hoogland (1953 a: 317)" authorityName="Hoogland" authorityPageNumber="317" authorityYear="1953" box="[392,771,1310,1337]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericea">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B1F37541FE7AFA93" box="[392,504,1311,1336]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sericea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B1857540FC81FA93" author="Hoogland, R. D." box="[510,771,1310,1337]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" pagination="310 - 319" refId="ref5831" refString="Hoogland, R. D. (1953 a) Florae Malesianae Precursores II. The Convolvulaceae of Malaysia IX. Blumea 7 (2): 310 - 319." type="journal article" year="1953">Hoogland (1953a: 317)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B3417541FB3AFA93" authority="Blume (1826: 1048)" authorityName="Blume (1826:" authorityPageNumber="1048" authorityYear="1048" box="[826,1208,1310,1336]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B3417541FC49FA93" box="[826,971,1311,1336]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. tomentosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB8A389FF9CFFD3B3A97540FB3AFA93" author="Blume, C. L." box="[978,1208,1310,1336]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" refId="ref5389" refString="Blume, C. L. (1826) Bijdragen tot de flora van Nederlandsch Indie, part 16. Batavia, Lands Drukkerij, iii + 123 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 6656" type="book" year="1826">Blume (1826: 1048)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The laminas of all of these species are soon glabrescent abaxially but, in addition, 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B343751DFC2BFAF7" authorityName="Hoogland" authorityYear="1953" box="[824,937,1347,1372]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericea">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B343751DFC2BFAF7" box="[824,937,1347,1372]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. sericea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a densely hairy ovary, and the hairs of 
<taxonomicName id="4C29A5FBFF9CFFD3B5E8751DFF79FA2B" authorityName="Blume (1826:" authorityYear="1048" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Erycibe" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentosa">
<emphasis id="B95D026AFF9CFFD3B5E8751DFF79FA2B" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">E. tomentosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are up to 
<quantity id="4CD1739DFF9CFFD3B1107538FE43FA2A" box="[363,449,1382,1409]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="3" pageNumber="106" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B96DE78FF9CFFD3B0C675D4FC28FA46" blockId="3.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="106">Field notes record that the flower buds are dull green, and the stem and leaves are ‘with brown furry indument’. The leaves have substantial and prominent insect damage with numerous sub-spherical to elliptic holes and leaf-miner damage (omitted from the line drawing to show venation more clearly).</paragraph>
